1
00:03:11,781 --> 00:03:14,147
Hi. I've got an appointment
with Mr. Ullman.

2
00:03:14,351 --> 00:03:16,285
My name is Jack Torrance.

3
00:03:16,486 --> 00:03:19,011
His office is the first door
on the left.

4
00:03:19,222 --> 00:03:20,450
Thank you.

5
00:03:37,807 --> 00:03:38,671
Mr. Ullman?

6
00:03:38,875 --> 00:03:40,137
I'm Jack Torrance.

7
00:03:40,343 --> 00:03:42,311
Come on in, Jack.

8
00:03:43,413 --> 00:03:45,938
- Very nice to meet you.
- Nice to meet you.

9
00:03:46,149 --> 00:03:47,673
This is my secretary, Susie.

10
00:03:48,084 --> 00:03:50,575
- Susie, how do you do?
- Any trouble finding us?

11
00:03:50,787 --> 00:03:53,620
No problem at all.
I made the trip in 3 1/2 hours.

12
00:03:53,823 --> 00:03:55,723
That's very good time.

13
00:03:56,059 --> 00:03:57,651
Sit down a minute, Jack.

14
00:03:57,894 --> 00:03:59,657
Just make yourself at home.

15
00:03:59,863 --> 00:04:01,125
Like some coffee?

16
00:04:01,331 --> 00:04:03,822
If you're having some,
I wouldn't mind. Thanks.

17
00:04:04,034 --> 00:04:05,023
- Susie.
- Sure.

18
00:04:05,235 --> 00:04:06,964
And ask Bill Watson to join us.

19
00:04:07,170 --> 00:04:08,603
Yes, I will.

20
00:04:19,482 --> 00:04:20,608
Mom?

21
00:04:21,484 --> 00:04:22,644
Yeah?

22
00:04:23,053 --> 00:04:26,682
Do you really want to go and live
in that hotel for the winter?

23
00:04:27,290 --> 00:04:28,655
Sure I do.

24
00:04:28,858 --> 00:04:30,792
It'll be lots of fun.

25
00:04:32,662 --> 00:04:34,755
Yeah. I guess so.

26
00:04:34,965 --> 00:04:39,129
Anyway, there's hardly anybody
to play with around here.

27
00:04:39,936 --> 00:04:43,428
I know. It always takes
a little time to make new friends.

28
00:04:45,041 --> 00:04:47,339
Yeah, I guess so.

29
00:04:48,111 --> 00:04:49,135
What about Tony?

30
00:04:49,346 --> 00:04:51,610
He's looking forward
to the hotel, I bet.

31
00:04:52,282 --> 00:04:54,648
No, I ain't, Mrs. Torrance.

32
00:04:55,051 --> 00:04:57,349
Now, come on, Tony.
Don't be silly.

33
00:04:57,887 --> 00:04:59,718
I don't want to go there.

34
00:05:00,357 --> 00:05:02,291
How come you don't want to go?

35
00:05:02,625 --> 00:05:04,525
I just don't.

36
00:05:04,794 --> 00:05:07,592
Did they give you
any idea in Denver...

37
00:05:07,797 --> 00:05:09,458
...about what the job entails?

38
00:05:09,666 --> 00:05:11,759
Only in a very general way.

39
00:05:14,237 --> 00:05:16,831
The winters can be
fantastically cruel.

40
00:05:17,040 --> 00:05:20,498
The basic idea is to cope
with the very costly damage...

41
00:05:20,710 --> 00:05:22,701
...and depreciation
which can occur.

42
00:05:22,912 --> 00:05:25,346
This consists mainly
of running the boiler...

43
00:05:25,548 --> 00:05:29,507
...heating different parts of the
hotel on a daily rotating basis...

44
00:05:29,719 --> 00:05:32,244
...repairing damage as it occurs...

45
00:05:32,455 --> 00:05:35,447
...and doing repairs so the
elements can't get a foothold.

46
00:05:36,526 --> 00:05:38,687
That sounds fine to me.

47
00:05:39,162 --> 00:05:42,131
Physically, it's not
a very demanding job.

48
00:05:42,332 --> 00:05:45,495
The only thing that can get a bit
trying here during the winter...

49
00:05:45,668 --> 00:05:48,159
...is a tremendous sense
of isolation.

50
00:05:49,439 --> 00:05:54,001
That just happens to be
exactly what I'm looking for.

51
00:05:54,344 --> 00:05:57,472
I'm outlining a new
writing project.

52
00:05:57,781 --> 00:06:01,080
Five months of peace
is just what I want.

53
00:06:01,851 --> 00:06:03,580
That's very good, Jack.

54
00:06:03,887 --> 00:06:07,050
Because, for some people...

55
00:06:07,257 --> 00:06:09,020
...solitude...

56
00:06:09,225 --> 00:06:10,852
...and isolation...

57
00:06:11,728 --> 00:06:13,992
...can, of itself, become a problem.

58
00:06:14,798 --> 00:06:16,390
Not for me.

59
00:06:16,933 --> 00:06:20,164
How about your wife and son?
Do you think they'll take to it?

60
00:06:21,971 --> 00:06:23,131
They'll love it.

61
00:06:23,339 --> 00:06:24,533
Great.

62
00:06:27,444 --> 00:06:30,675
Before I turn you over to Bill...

63
00:06:30,880 --> 00:06:34,372
...there's one other thing I think
we should talk about.

64
00:06:34,584 --> 00:06:36,017
Not to sound melodramatic...

65
00:06:36,219 --> 00:06:38,779
...but it's been known to
give a few people...

66
00:06:38,988 --> 00:06:41,183
...second thoughts about the job.

67
00:06:41,891 --> 00:06:43,552
I'm intrigued.

68
00:06:43,760 --> 00:06:46,092
I don't suppose they
said anything in Denver...

69
00:06:46,296 --> 00:06:50,255
...about the tragedy we had up here
during the winter of 1970.

70
00:06:50,867 --> 00:06:52,858
I don't believe they did.

71
00:06:55,438 --> 00:06:57,133
My predecessor in this job...

72
00:06:57,874 --> 00:07:01,105
...hired a man named Charles Grady
as the winter caretaker.

73
00:07:01,311 --> 00:07:04,838
He came up with his wife and
two little girls of about 8 and 10.

74
00:07:05,048 --> 00:07:08,040
He had a good employment record,
good references.

75
00:07:08,251 --> 00:07:10,515
And from what I've been told,
he seemed...

76
00:07:10,720 --> 00:07:13,416
...like a completely
normal individual.

77
00:07:13,623 --> 00:07:15,989
But at some point
during the winter...

78
00:07:16,192 --> 00:07:19,821
...he must have suffered some kind
of a complete mental breakdown.

79
00:07:20,029 --> 00:07:22,395
He ran amuck...

80
00:07:25,802 --> 00:07:27,997
...and killed his family
with an ax.

81
00:07:29,272 --> 00:07:33,902
Stacked them neatly in a room
in the west wing, and then...

82
00:07:34,711 --> 00:07:38,408
...he put both barrels
of his shotgun in his mouth.

83
00:07:39,649 --> 00:07:41,446
The police thought...

84
00:07:41,651 --> 00:07:45,712
...that it was what the old-timers
used to call cabin fever.

85
00:07:45,922 --> 00:07:48,948
A kind of claustrophobic reaction
which can occur...

86
00:07:49,159 --> 00:07:53,289
...when people are shut in together
over long periods of time.

87
00:07:58,368 --> 00:07:59,801
That is...

88
00:08:00,003 --> 00:08:01,527
...quite a story.

89
00:08:02,839 --> 00:08:04,306
Yeah, it is.

90
00:08:05,408 --> 00:08:08,707
It's still hard for me to believe
it actually happened here.

91
00:08:09,045 --> 00:08:10,740
But it did.

92
00:08:12,515 --> 00:08:16,542
I think you can appreciate
why I wanted to tell you about it.

93
00:08:17,086 --> 00:08:19,577
I certainly can.

94
00:08:20,089 --> 00:08:22,649
I also understand
why your people in Denver...

95
00:08:22,859 --> 00:08:25,123
...left it for you to tell me.

96
00:08:26,329 --> 00:08:29,025
Obviously, some people
can be put off...

97
00:08:29,232 --> 00:08:33,328
...from staying in a place where
something like that happened.

98
00:08:33,536 --> 00:08:38,439
You can rest assured that's not
going to happen with me.

99
00:08:38,641 --> 00:08:42,304
And as far as my wife
is concerned...

100
00:08:42,512 --> 00:08:46,346
...I'm sure she'll be absolutely
fascinated when I tell her.

101
00:08:46,549 --> 00:08:49,382
She's a confirmed ghost story...

102
00:08:49,586 --> 00:08:52,020
...and horror film addict.

103
00:08:56,859 --> 00:09:00,556
Tony, do you think
Dad'll get the job?

104
00:09:01,965 --> 00:09:04,160
He already did.

105
00:09:04,601 --> 00:09:08,332
He's going to phone Wendy up
in a few minutes to tell her.

106
00:09:23,052 --> 00:09:25,714
- Hi, babe.
- Hi, hon. How's it going?

107
00:09:25,922 --> 00:09:29,517
Great. I'm at the hotel and
I still have a lot to go through.

108
00:09:29,726 --> 00:09:32,854
I don't think I can get home
before 9:00 or 10:00.

109
00:09:33,062 --> 00:09:34,552
Sounds like you got the job.

110
00:09:34,764 --> 00:09:37,460
Right. It's a beautiful place.

111
00:09:37,667 --> 00:09:39,794
You and Danny are going to love it.

112
00:09:41,271 --> 00:09:44,172
Tony, why don't you want to go
to the hotel?

113
00:09:44,440 --> 00:09:46,169
I don't know.

114
00:09:47,243 --> 00:09:50,770
You do too know.
Now come on, tell me.

115
00:09:51,347 --> 00:09:53,406
I don't want to.

116
00:09:54,117 --> 00:09:55,379
Please.

117
00:09:56,619 --> 00:09:57,745
No.

118
00:09:58,054 --> 00:10:00,147
Now, Tony, tell me.

119
00:10:57,313 --> 00:11:01,477
We must really be high up.
The air feels so different.

120
00:11:07,123 --> 00:11:08,351
Dad?

121
00:11:11,160 --> 00:11:12,855
I'm hungry.

122
00:11:14,697 --> 00:11:17,427
You should've eaten your breakfast.

123
00:11:18,267 --> 00:11:21,168
We'll get you something
as soon as we get to the hotel.

124
00:11:21,371 --> 00:11:22,998
Okay, Mom.

125
00:11:24,440 --> 00:11:28,570
Wasn't it around here that
the Donner party got snowbound?

126
00:11:30,313 --> 00:11:33,805
I think that was farther west,
in the Sierras.

127
00:11:35,284 --> 00:11:37,718
What was the Donner party?

128
00:11:39,655 --> 00:11:43,921
They were a party of settlers
in covered wagon times.

129
00:11:44,160 --> 00:11:47,425
They got snowbound one winter
in the mountains.

130
00:11:47,630 --> 00:11:51,828
They had to resort to cannibalism
in order to stay alive.

131
00:11:52,969 --> 00:11:55,870
You mean they ate each other up?

132
00:11:56,072 --> 00:11:59,166
They had to in order to survive.

133
00:11:59,375 --> 00:12:00,603
Jack.

134
00:12:00,810 --> 00:12:01,902
Don't worry, Mom.

135
00:12:02,111 --> 00:12:06,445
I know all about cannibalism.
I saw it on TV.

136
00:12:06,649 --> 00:12:09,277
See, it's okay.

137
00:12:09,485 --> 00:12:11,919
He saw it all on the television.

138
00:12:42,618 --> 00:12:44,449
- What time does the plane leave?
- 8:30.

139
00:12:44,654 --> 00:12:47,418
That gives us plenty of time
to go over everything.

140
00:12:47,623 --> 00:12:49,557
- Goodbye, Mr. Ullman.
- Bye.

141
00:12:49,759 --> 00:12:52,887
Good morning. I hope you
haven't been waiting too long.

142
00:12:53,095 --> 00:12:55,723
No problem. We had time
to grab a bite to eat.

143
00:12:55,932 --> 00:12:58,833
Good. Glad you made it
before they shut down the kitchen.

144
00:12:59,035 --> 00:13:00,764
Is your family
having a look around?

145
00:13:00,970 --> 00:13:04,337
No, my son's
discovered the games room.

146
00:13:04,540 --> 00:13:07,634
- Has your luggage been brought in?
- Right there.

147
00:13:08,211 --> 00:13:10,179
In view of all we have
to cover today...

148
00:13:10,379 --> 00:13:14,042
...I suggest we have a quick look
at your apartment and get started.

149
00:13:14,250 --> 00:13:17,014
Have the Torrances' things
brought to their apartment.

150
00:13:17,220 --> 00:13:19,916
I'd better collect my family first.

151
00:13:28,064 --> 00:13:30,430
This is our Colorado Lounge.

152
00:13:30,633 --> 00:13:33,067
It's beautiful.

153
00:13:33,469 --> 00:13:35,334
My God!

154
00:13:35,538 --> 00:13:38,098
This place is fantastic,
isn't it, hon?

155
00:13:38,307 --> 00:13:39,638
It sure is.

156
00:14:32,562 --> 00:14:35,122
This is the staff wing
of the hotel.

157
00:14:36,098 --> 00:14:39,431
None of the other bedrooms
are heated during the winter.

158
00:14:39,669 --> 00:14:42,570
- Goodbye, Mr. Ullman.
- Goodbye, girls.

159
00:14:42,805 --> 00:14:44,796
And here are your quarters.

160
00:14:45,207 --> 00:14:47,801
Living room, bedroom, bathroom.

161
00:14:48,010 --> 00:14:50,501
And a small bedroom for your son.

162
00:14:54,116 --> 00:14:56,141
Perfect for a child.

163
00:15:04,694 --> 00:15:06,787
When was the Overlook built?

164
00:15:07,797 --> 00:15:10,027
Construction started in 1907.

165
00:15:10,232 --> 00:15:12,200
It was finished in 1909.

166
00:15:12,401 --> 00:15:15,063
The site's supposed to be
on an Indian burial ground.

167
00:15:15,271 --> 00:15:16,898
They actually had to repel...

168
00:15:17,106 --> 00:15:20,007
...a few Indian attacks as they
were building it.

169
00:15:20,610 --> 00:15:22,510
That's our Snowcat.

170
00:15:23,212 --> 00:15:25,237
Can you both drive a car?

171
00:15:25,781 --> 00:15:29,342
That's fine. Basically the Snowcat
operates very much like a car.

172
00:15:29,552 --> 00:15:31,281
You'll get the hang of it.

173
00:15:32,054 --> 00:15:33,681
This is the kitchen, huh?

174
00:15:33,889 --> 00:15:35,481
This is it.

175
00:15:35,691 --> 00:15:38,626
How do you like it, Danny?
Is it big enough for you?

176
00:15:39,462 --> 00:15:41,657
It's the biggest place I ever seen.

177
00:15:41,897 --> 00:15:44,229
This whole place
is such an enormous maze.

178
00:15:44,433 --> 00:15:47,994
I'll have to leave a trail of
breadcrumbs every time I come in.

179
00:15:48,904 --> 00:15:50,769
Don't let it get you down.

180
00:15:50,973 --> 00:15:53,464
It's big, but it ain't
nothing but a kitchen.

181
00:15:53,676 --> 00:15:55,871
A lot of this stuff
you'll never have to touch.

182
00:15:56,078 --> 00:15:58,308
I wouldn't know
what to do with it if I did.

183
00:15:58,514 --> 00:16:01,642
One thing for sure, you don't
have to worry about food.

184
00:16:01,851 --> 00:16:06,515
You folks could eat here for a year
and never have the same menu twice.

185
00:16:06,722 --> 00:16:09,816
Right here is
our walk-in freezer.

186
00:16:10,960 --> 00:16:14,020
This is where we keep
all of our meat.

187
00:16:14,230 --> 00:16:16,221
You got 15 rib roasts...

188
00:16:16,432 --> 00:16:18,559
...30 ten-pound bags of hamburger.

189
00:16:18,768 --> 00:16:21,828
We got 12 turkeys,
about 40 chickens...

190
00:16:22,038 --> 00:16:25,132
...50 sirloin steaks,
two dozen of pork roast...

191
00:16:25,341 --> 00:16:28,310
...and 20 legs of lamb.
Do you like lamb, Doc?

192
00:16:29,545 --> 00:16:31,911
You don't?
What's your favorite food, then?

193
00:16:32,114 --> 00:16:33,979
French fries and ketchup.

194
00:16:34,717 --> 00:16:36,708
I think we can
manage that too, Doc.

195
00:16:36,919 --> 00:16:38,648
Come along, now.
Watch your step.

196
00:16:45,394 --> 00:16:46,952
How'd you know we call him Doc?

197
00:16:47,163 --> 00:16:51,190
- Beg your pardon?
- Doc. You called Danny "Doc" twice.

198
00:16:51,400 --> 00:16:52,799
I did?

199
00:16:53,602 --> 00:16:56,730
We call him Doc sometimes,
like in the Bugs Bunny cartoons.

200
00:16:56,939 --> 00:16:58,201
But how did you know?

201
00:16:58,407 --> 00:17:00,932
I guess I probably
heard you call him that.

202
00:17:01,143 --> 00:17:03,407
It's possible.
But I honestly don't remember...

203
00:17:03,612 --> 00:17:05,807
...calling him that
since we've been with you.

204
00:17:06,015 --> 00:17:08,210
Anyway, he looks
like a Doc, doesn't he?

205
00:17:09,652 --> 00:17:11,085
What's up, Doc?

206
00:17:12,922 --> 00:17:15,117
Now, this is the storeroom.

207
00:17:16,859 --> 00:17:18,690
In here is where we keep...

208
00:17:18,894 --> 00:17:21,692
...all the dried goods
and the canned goods.

209
00:17:21,897 --> 00:17:24,331
We got canned fruits
and vegetables...

210
00:17:24,533 --> 00:17:28,333
...canned fish and meats,
hot and cold cereals.

211
00:17:28,537 --> 00:17:31,734
Post Toasties, Corn Flakes,
Sugar Puffs...

212
00:17:31,941 --> 00:17:35,968
...Rice Krispies, oatmeal,
Wheatena and Cream of Wheat.

213
00:17:36,212 --> 00:17:38,646
You got a dozen jugs
of black molasses.

214
00:17:38,848 --> 00:17:42,045
We got 60 boxes of dried milk...

215
00:17:49,692 --> 00:17:52,160
How'd you like some ice cream, Doc?

216
00:17:54,563 --> 00:17:56,554
Sociables, finger rolls...

217
00:17:56,766 --> 00:17:58,290
...and 7 kinds of what have you.

218
00:17:58,501 --> 00:18:02,028
Now, we've got dried peaches,
dried apricots...

219
00:18:02,238 --> 00:18:05,332
...dried raisins and dried prunes.

220
00:18:05,541 --> 00:18:09,841
You know, you got to keep regular
if you want to be happy.

221
00:18:12,748 --> 00:18:14,375
- How're you getting on?
- Fine.

222
00:18:14,583 --> 00:18:18,144
Can we borrow Mrs. Torrance?
We're on our way to the basement.

223
00:18:18,354 --> 00:18:20,288
I promise we won't
keep her very long.

224
00:18:20,489 --> 00:18:23,686
No problem, Mr. Ullman. I was just
getting to the ice cream.

225
00:18:23,893 --> 00:18:25,758
You like ice cream, Doc?

226
00:18:26,629 --> 00:18:27,596
I thought you did.

227
00:18:27,797 --> 00:18:30,857
You folks mind if I give Danny
some ice cream while we wait?

228
00:18:31,066 --> 00:18:32,897
- Not at all.
- We don't mind.

229
00:18:33,102 --> 00:18:35,297
- Good.
- Sound good to you, Doc?

230
00:18:35,504 --> 00:18:37,563
Okay, you behave yourself.

231
00:18:40,576 --> 00:18:42,441
What kind of ice cream
do you like?

232
00:18:42,645 --> 00:18:43,543
Chocolate.

233
00:18:43,746 --> 00:18:46,715
Chocolate it shall be.
Come on, son.

234
00:18:51,287 --> 00:18:53,278
It's amazing, all this
activity today.

235
00:18:53,489 --> 00:18:56,287
The guests and some staff
left yesterday, but the...

236
00:18:56,492 --> 00:18:57,925
...last day's always hectic.

237
00:18:58,127 --> 00:19:01,187
Everybody wants to be on their way
as early as possible.

238
00:19:01,397 --> 00:19:05,424
By 5:00 tonight, you'll never
know anybody was ever here.

239
00:19:05,634 --> 00:19:07,693
Just like a ghost ship, huh?

240
00:19:13,375 --> 00:19:16,344
Do you know how I knew
your name was Doc?

241
00:19:22,918 --> 00:19:25,318
You know what I'm
talking about, don't you?

242
00:19:32,294 --> 00:19:35,786
I can remember when I was
a little boy...

243
00:19:36,198 --> 00:19:38,723
...my grandmother and I
could hold conversations...

244
00:19:38,934 --> 00:19:42,768
...entirely without ever
opening our mouths.

245
00:19:43,839 --> 00:19:46,137
She called it "shining."

246
00:19:47,643 --> 00:19:50,373
And for a long time I thought
it was just the two of us...

247
00:19:50,579 --> 00:19:53,104
...that had "the shine" to us.

248
00:19:53,816 --> 00:19:56,808
Just like you probably thought
you was the only one.

249
00:19:57,486 --> 00:19:59,351
But there are other folks...

250
00:19:59,555 --> 00:20:03,286
...though mostly they don't
know it, or don't believe it.

251
00:20:07,963 --> 00:20:10,397
How long have you
been able to do it?

252
00:20:15,604 --> 00:20:18,004
Why don't you want
to talk about it?

253
00:20:23,245 --> 00:20:25,304
I'm not supposed to.

254
00:20:26,882 --> 00:20:29,407
Who says you ain't supposed to?

255
00:20:32,855 --> 00:20:34,254
Tony.

256
00:20:36,225 --> 00:20:37,886
Who's Tony?

257
00:20:40,362 --> 00:20:43,763
Tony's the little boy
that lives in my mouth.

258
00:20:45,701 --> 00:20:47,726
Is Tony the one
that...

259
00:20:47,937 --> 00:20:49,495
...tells you things?

260
00:20:54,043 --> 00:20:56,409
How does he tell you things?

261
00:20:58,247 --> 00:21:02,547
It's like I go to sleep,
and he shows me things.

262
00:21:02,751 --> 00:21:06,847
But when I wake up,
I can't remember everything.

263
00:21:08,691 --> 00:21:12,388
Does your mom and dad
know about Tony?

264
00:21:15,698 --> 00:21:18,258
Do they know he tells you things?

265
00:21:19,134 --> 00:21:22,069
Tony told me never to tell them.

266
00:21:24,206 --> 00:21:27,573
Has Tony ever told you
anything about this place?

267
00:21:27,776 --> 00:21:30,336
About the Overlook Hotel?

268
00:21:33,615 --> 00:21:35,173
I don't know.

269
00:21:36,085 --> 00:21:40,112
Now think real hard, Doc. Think.

270
00:21:45,394 --> 00:21:47,794
Is there something bad here?

271
00:21:59,408 --> 00:22:01,842
You know, Doc,
when something happens...

272
00:22:02,044 --> 00:22:05,673
...it can leave a trace
of itself behind.

273
00:22:06,448 --> 00:22:08,006
Say, like...

274
00:22:08,217 --> 00:22:11,277
...if someone burns toast.

275
00:22:13,389 --> 00:22:18,053
Maybe things that happen
leave other kind of traces behind.

276
00:22:19,228 --> 00:22:22,664
Not things that anyone
can notice.

277
00:22:22,865 --> 00:22:27,666
But things that people
who shine can see.

278
00:22:28,771 --> 00:22:32,070
Just like they can see things
that haven't happened yet...

279
00:22:34,343 --> 00:22:38,507
...sometimes they can see things
that happened a long time ago.

280
00:22:40,049 --> 00:22:42,916
I think a lot of things
happened right here...

281
00:22:43,118 --> 00:22:46,815
...in this particular hotel
over the years.

282
00:22:47,356 --> 00:22:49,756
And not all of them
was good.

283
00:22:53,062 --> 00:22:55,690
What about room 237?

284
00:22:59,034 --> 00:23:01,229
Room 237?

285
00:23:02,538 --> 00:23:05,632
You're scared of room 237,
ain't you?

286
00:23:07,409 --> 00:23:08,876
No, I ain't.

287
00:23:10,379 --> 00:23:14,213
Mr. Hallorann, what is in room 237?

288
00:23:15,551 --> 00:23:16,916
Nothing.

289
00:23:17,352 --> 00:23:20,583
There ain't nothing in room 237.

290
00:23:20,789 --> 00:23:24,020
But you ain't got no business
going in there anyway.

291
00:23:24,226 --> 00:23:26,353
So stay out.

292
00:23:26,562 --> 00:23:29,053
You understand? Stay out!

293
00:24:45,307 --> 00:24:47,036
Good morning, hon.

294
00:24:49,044 --> 00:24:50,807
Your breakfast is ready.

295
00:24:51,580 --> 00:24:53,207
What time is it?

296
00:24:53,415 --> 00:24:55,280
It's about 11:30.

297
00:24:57,186 --> 00:24:58,778
Jesus.

298
00:24:59,721 --> 00:25:02,155
I guess we've been
staying up too late.

299
00:25:02,457 --> 00:25:03,890
I know it.

300
00:25:05,194 --> 00:25:08,061
I made them just the way
you like them, sunny-side up.

301
00:25:08,363 --> 00:25:09,921
Nice.

302
00:25:12,201 --> 00:25:13,998
It's really pretty outside.

303
00:25:14,203 --> 00:25:17,434
How about taking me for a walk
after you finish your breakfast?

304
00:25:18,040 --> 00:25:22,374
I suppose I ought to try
to do some writing first.

305
00:25:23,812 --> 00:25:25,473
Any ideas yet?

306
00:25:26,481 --> 00:25:28,142
Lots of ideas.

307
00:25:28,350 --> 00:25:29,874
No good ones.

308
00:25:30,352 --> 00:25:32,820
Something will come.

309
00:25:33,322 --> 00:25:37,258
It's just a matter of settling into
the habit of writing every day.

310
00:25:38,827 --> 00:25:40,522
That's all it is.

311
00:25:59,881 --> 00:26:02,441
- All right.
- And you're going to lose.

312
00:26:02,651 --> 00:26:05,779
And I'm going to get you.
You'd better run fast!

313
00:26:10,792 --> 00:26:11,918
Look out!

314
00:26:12,127 --> 00:26:13,992
I'm coming in close.

315
00:26:14,196 --> 00:26:16,687
Loser has to keep America clean.

316
00:26:16,932 --> 00:26:18,559
Keep America clean.

317
00:26:19,568 --> 00:26:21,035
Danny, you win.

318
00:26:21,370 --> 00:26:23,702
Let's take the rest
of this walking.

319
00:26:26,241 --> 00:26:27,640
Give me your hand.

320
00:26:30,279 --> 00:26:32,076
Isn't it beautiful?

321
00:26:49,831 --> 00:26:51,196
Dead end.

322
00:27:48,657 --> 00:27:50,284
We made it.

323
00:27:50,792 --> 00:27:52,020
Isn't it beautiful?

324
00:28:13,715 --> 00:28:15,546
It's so pretty.

325
00:28:20,122 --> 00:28:23,091
I didn't think it was
going to be this big. Did you?

326
00:31:01,082 --> 00:31:02,515
Hi, hon.

327
00:31:06,121 --> 00:31:07,520
How's it going?

328
00:31:10,091 --> 00:31:11,251
Fine.

329
00:31:13,361 --> 00:31:14,919
Get a lot written today?

330
00:31:21,970 --> 00:31:24,530
The weather forecast
said it's going to snow tonight.

331
00:31:29,744 --> 00:31:32,076
What do you want me
to do about it?

332
00:31:34,215 --> 00:31:36,376
Come on, hon.

333
00:31:36,718 --> 00:31:38,743
Don't be so grouchy.

334
00:31:39,154 --> 00:31:40,485
I'm not...

335
00:31:40,855 --> 00:31:42,049
...being grouchy.

336
00:31:42,257 --> 00:31:45,055
I just want to finish my work.

337
00:31:48,563 --> 00:31:50,963
Okay. I understand.

338
00:31:51,199 --> 00:31:53,793
I'll come back later
with a couple of sandwiches.

339
00:31:54,002 --> 00:31:56,470
Maybe you'll let me
read something then.

340
00:31:59,674 --> 00:32:00,766
Wendy...

341
00:32:00,976 --> 00:32:03,570
...let me explain something to you.

342
00:32:04,479 --> 00:32:08,347
When you come in and interrupt,
you're breaking my concentration.

343
00:32:08,550 --> 00:32:09,983
You're distracting me...

344
00:32:10,185 --> 00:32:13,621
...and it will then take me time
to get back to where I was.

345
00:32:13,822 --> 00:32:15,255
Understand?

346
00:32:18,727 --> 00:32:19,887
Fine.

347
00:32:21,062 --> 00:32:22,791
We're going to make a new rule:

348
00:32:22,998 --> 00:32:24,431
Whenever I'm in here...

349
00:32:24,633 --> 00:32:26,897
...and you hear me typing...

350
00:32:28,703 --> 00:32:31,638
...or whatever the fuck
you hear me doing in here...

351
00:32:31,840 --> 00:32:34,138
...when I'm in here,
that means I am working.

352
00:32:34,342 --> 00:32:36,572
That means don't come in.

353
00:32:36,778 --> 00:32:39,042
Now, do you think
you can handle that?

354
00:32:43,685 --> 00:32:44,811
Fine.

355
00:32:45,854 --> 00:32:49,153
Why don't you start right now
and get the fuck out of here?

356
00:33:14,516 --> 00:33:15,574
Missed!

357
00:33:21,156 --> 00:33:21,986
Don't have!

358
00:33:22,223 --> 00:33:23,952
No fair anymore.

359
00:34:31,392 --> 00:34:32,689
I knew it.

360
00:35:02,957 --> 00:35:06,449
This is IKDIK 12 calling IKDIK 1.

361
00:35:08,963 --> 00:35:12,660
KDK 12 to KDK 1.

362
00:35:12,867 --> 00:35:15,995
This is KDK 1.
We're receiving you. Over.

363
00:35:16,371 --> 00:35:19,499
Hi, this is Wendy Torrance
at the Overlook Hotel.

364
00:35:20,074 --> 00:35:22,872
Hi, how are you folks
getting on up there? Over.

365
00:35:23,144 --> 00:35:24,475
We're just fine.

366
00:35:24,679 --> 00:35:27,147
But our telephones
aren't doing too well.

367
00:35:27,348 --> 00:35:30,374
Are the lines down,
by any chance? Over.

368
00:35:31,019 --> 00:35:34,819
Yes, quite a few of them are down
due to the storm. Over.

369
00:35:35,123 --> 00:35:38,320
Any chance of them
being repaired soon? Over.

370
00:35:38,526 --> 00:35:39,686
Well, I wouldn't like to say.

371
00:35:39,894 --> 00:35:43,330
Most winters they stay that way
until spring. Over.

372
00:35:43,832 --> 00:35:47,233
Boy, this storm is really something,
isn't it? Over.

373
00:35:47,702 --> 00:35:50,603
Yes. It's one of the worst we've
had for years.

374
00:35:51,172 --> 00:35:54,369
Is there anything else we can
do for you, Mrs. Torrance?

375
00:35:54,843 --> 00:35:57,004
I suppose not. Over.

376
00:35:57,612 --> 00:36:00,911
If you folks have any problems
up there, just give us a call.

377
00:36:01,115 --> 00:36:02,412
And, Mrs. Torrance?

378
00:36:02,617 --> 00:36:06,815
It might be a good idea if you
leave your radio on all the time.

379
00:36:07,655 --> 00:36:09,145
Okay. We'll do that.

380
00:36:09,357 --> 00:36:11,416
It was real nice talking to you.

381
00:36:11,626 --> 00:36:14,254
Bye. Over and out.

382
00:36:49,163 --> 00:36:51,358
Hello, Danny.

383
00:36:56,638 --> 00:36:59,072
Come and play with us.

384
00:37:03,945 --> 00:37:06,709
Come and play with us, Danny.

385
00:37:08,549 --> 00:37:10,414
Forever...

386
00:37:12,186 --> 00:37:13,949
...and ever...

387
00:37:14,889 --> 00:37:16,914
...and ever.

388
00:37:48,389 --> 00:37:50,016
Tony...

389
00:37:51,025 --> 00:37:53,050
...I'm scared.

390
00:37:58,533 --> 00:38:02,094
Remember what Mr. Hallorann said.

391
00:38:03,705 --> 00:38:07,607
It's just like
pictures in a book, Danny.

392
00:38:07,809 --> 00:38:09,970
It isn't real.

393
00:39:04,420 --> 00:39:07,583
Can I go to my room
and get my fire engine?

394
00:39:11,327 --> 00:39:13,522
Come here for a minute first.

395
00:39:50,533 --> 00:39:52,330
How's it going, Doc?

396
00:39:56,906 --> 00:39:58,703
Having a good time?

397
00:40:00,777 --> 00:40:02,244
Yes, Dad.

398
00:40:05,148 --> 00:40:06,376
Good.

399
00:40:08,584 --> 00:40:10,745
I want you to
have a good time.

400
00:40:11,454 --> 00:40:13,081
I am, Dad.

401
00:40:23,533 --> 00:40:25,330
Do you feel bad?

402
00:40:31,274 --> 00:40:33,572
I'm just a little bit tired.

403
00:40:35,144 --> 00:40:37,704
Then why don't you
go to sleep?

404
00:40:41,284 --> 00:40:42,842
I can't.

405
00:40:44,320 --> 00:40:46,618
I got too much to do.

406
00:40:55,932 --> 00:40:58,196
Do you like this hotel?

407
00:41:04,207 --> 00:41:05,606
I do.

408
00:41:06,576 --> 00:41:07,907
I love it.

409
00:41:10,112 --> 00:41:11,443
Don't you?

410
00:41:13,816 --> 00:41:15,306
I guess so.

411
00:41:17,954 --> 00:41:19,148
Good.

412
00:41:22,358 --> 00:41:24,690
I want you to like it here.

413
00:41:28,664 --> 00:41:32,065
I wish we could stay here
forever...

414
00:41:32,268 --> 00:41:34,065
...and ever...

415
00:41:34,737 --> 00:41:36,068
...and ever.

416
00:41:41,510 --> 00:41:42,534
What?

417
00:41:43,813 --> 00:41:46,907
You would never hurt Mommy or me,
would you?

418
00:41:52,388 --> 00:41:53,878
What do you mean?

419
00:41:58,995 --> 00:42:01,589
Did your mother ever
say that to you?

420
00:42:02,265 --> 00:42:04,062
That I would hurt you?

421
00:42:04,834 --> 00:42:06,199
No, Dad.

422
00:42:08,371 --> 00:42:09,929
You sure?

423
00:42:10,473 --> 00:42:12,031
Yes, Dad.

424
00:42:16,846 --> 00:42:18,871
I love you, Danny.

425
00:42:20,082 --> 00:42:22,676
I love you
more than anything else...

426
00:42:22,885 --> 00:42:25,445
...in the whole world...

427
00:42:26,222 --> 00:42:29,282
...and I would never do anything
to hurt you...

428
00:42:29,592 --> 00:42:30,820
...never.

429
00:42:31,694 --> 00:42:33,753
You know that, don't you?

430
00:42:34,230 --> 00:42:35,788
Yes, Dad.

431
00:42:36,732 --> 00:42:37,824
Good.

432
00:44:05,755 --> 00:44:07,518
Mom, are you in there?

433
00:45:26,769 --> 00:45:27,827
What happened?

434
00:45:28,037 --> 00:45:29,265
Honey...

435
00:45:30,139 --> 00:45:31,538
...what's wrong?

436
00:45:39,715 --> 00:45:41,114
I had the most...

437
00:45:41,317 --> 00:45:43,911
...terrible nightmare I ever had.

438
00:45:45,855 --> 00:45:48,790
- It was the most horrible dream.
- It's okay, it's okay now.

439
00:45:49,992 --> 00:45:51,357
Really.

440
00:45:55,631 --> 00:45:57,223
I dreamed that I...

441
00:45:57,433 --> 00:45:59,867
...that I killed
you and Danny.

442
00:46:02,605 --> 00:46:04,835
But I didn't just kill you.

443
00:46:06,142 --> 00:46:08,906
I cut you up
into little pieces.

444
00:46:11,580 --> 00:46:13,104
My God.

445
00:46:13,816 --> 00:46:16,376
I must be losing my mind.

446
00:46:18,654 --> 00:46:21,282
Everything's going to be
all right.

447
00:46:23,392 --> 00:46:26,088
Come on. Let's get up
off the floor.

448
00:46:33,936 --> 00:46:36,234
There. Now sit up.

449
00:46:36,872 --> 00:46:38,169
It's okay.

450
00:46:39,275 --> 00:46:40,708
It's okay.

451
00:46:44,780 --> 00:46:45,974
Danny!

452
00:46:46,282 --> 00:46:48,216
Everything's okay!

453
00:46:48,417 --> 00:46:51,580
Just go play in your room
for a while.

454
00:46:51,921 --> 00:46:53,980
Your dad's just got
a headache.

455
00:46:55,291 --> 00:46:58,317
Danny, mind what I say.
Go play in your room.

456
00:47:00,296 --> 00:47:03,231
Honey, let me just go
get him out of here.

457
00:47:03,432 --> 00:47:04,956
I'll be right back.

458
00:47:06,869 --> 00:47:08,928
Why don't you mind me?

459
00:47:15,544 --> 00:47:17,375
Oh, my God.

460
00:47:18,581 --> 00:47:20,981
What happened to your neck?

461
00:47:22,918 --> 00:47:25,045
What happened to your neck?

462
00:47:54,016 --> 00:47:55,984
You did this to him...

463
00:47:56,418 --> 00:47:57,851
...didn't you?!

464
00:47:59,688 --> 00:48:01,747
You son of a bitch!

465
00:48:01,957 --> 00:48:03,822
You did this to him!

466
00:48:04,026 --> 00:48:05,459
Didn't you?!

467
00:48:06,795 --> 00:48:08,456
How could you?!

468
00:48:08,697 --> 00:48:10,426
How could you?!

469
00:49:40,289 --> 00:49:43,383
God! I'd give anything
for a drink.

470
00:49:46,028 --> 00:49:48,929
I'd give my goddamn soul...

471
00:49:49,131 --> 00:49:51,622
...for just a glass of beer.

472
00:50:06,615 --> 00:50:08,105
Hi, Lloyd.

473
00:50:11,653 --> 00:50:14,053
A little slow tonight,
isn't it?

474
00:50:18,927 --> 00:50:21,191
Yes it is, Mr. Torrance.

475
00:50:23,265 --> 00:50:24,732
What will it be?

476
00:50:26,402 --> 00:50:29,371
I'm awfully glad
you asked me that, Lloyd...

477
00:50:29,571 --> 00:50:32,904
...because I just happen to have
two twenties...

478
00:50:33,108 --> 00:50:36,009
...and two tens
right here in my wallet.

479
00:50:36,211 --> 00:50:39,476
I was afraid they were
going to be there until next April.

480
00:50:40,182 --> 00:50:42,013
So here's what:

481
00:50:42,317 --> 00:50:44,615
You slip me a bottle of bourbon...

482
00:50:44,820 --> 00:50:47,618
...a little glass and some ice.

483
00:50:47,823 --> 00:50:49,848
You can do that,
can't you, Lloyd?

484
00:50:50,292 --> 00:50:52,658
You're not too busy, are you?

485
00:50:53,228 --> 00:50:55,719
No, sir.
I'm not busy at all.

486
00:50:56,231 --> 00:50:57,789
Good man.

487
00:50:58,100 --> 00:50:59,192
You set them up...

488
00:50:59,468 --> 00:51:02,335
...and I'll knock them back,
one by one.

489
00:51:03,472 --> 00:51:06,407
White man's burden,
Lloyd, my man.

490
00:51:06,608 --> 00:51:08,769
White man's burden.

491
00:51:14,850 --> 00:51:15,976
Say, Lloyd...

492
00:51:16,185 --> 00:51:18,949
...it seems I'm temporarily light.

493
00:51:19,288 --> 00:51:21,722
How's my credit
in this joint, anyway?

494
00:51:21,990 --> 00:51:24,356
Your credit's fine, Mr. Torrance.

495
00:51:25,060 --> 00:51:26,687
That's swell.

496
00:51:26,895 --> 00:51:28,590
I like you, Lloyd.

497
00:51:28,797 --> 00:51:30,458
I always liked you.

498
00:51:30,666 --> 00:51:32,998
You were always the best of them.

499
00:51:33,202 --> 00:51:35,568
Best goddamned bartender...

500
00:51:35,771 --> 00:51:38,706
...from Timbuktu
to Portland, Maine.

501
00:51:38,907 --> 00:51:41,137
Or Portland, Oregon,
for that matter.

502
00:51:41,410 --> 00:51:43,207
Thank you for saying so.

503
00:51:55,691 --> 00:51:58,922
I never laid a hand on him,
goddamn it.

504
00:51:59,127 --> 00:52:00,754
I didn't.

505
00:52:02,798 --> 00:52:07,394
I wouldn't touch one hair
on his goddamn little head.

506
00:52:08,003 --> 00:52:11,131
I love the little
son of a bitch.

507
00:52:12,741 --> 00:52:15,574
I'd do anything for him.

508
00:52:15,777 --> 00:52:18,575
Any fucking thing for him.

509
00:52:22,651 --> 00:52:25,211
But that bitch!

510
00:52:26,221 --> 00:52:27,916
As long as I live...

511
00:52:28,190 --> 00:52:31,591
...she'll never let me forget
what happened.

512
00:52:41,203 --> 00:52:44,036
I did hurt him once, okay?

513
00:52:44,406 --> 00:52:46,465
It was an accident.

514
00:52:46,775 --> 00:52:49,369
Completely unintentional.

515
00:52:50,646 --> 00:52:52,876
It could have happened
to anybody.

516
00:52:54,616 --> 00:52:58,074
And it was three goddamn
years ago!

517
00:52:58,287 --> 00:53:01,120
The little fucker had thrown all my
papers all over the floor.

518
00:53:01,323 --> 00:53:03,791
All I tried to do was pull him up.

519
00:53:06,562 --> 00:53:11,261
